,Not Recommended,280520,32319958,Posted: 10 June,all,Kreegath,"Crea isn't worth your time or your money. It's deeply flawed in every major aspect of the Terraria-like genre. There's no incentive to build anything. There's no incentive to explore. There's no joy in spelunking. There's no functioning combat system. There's no point in the talent system or the level system, other than pad the grind time. There's no functioning boss system. Crea is glitched and bugged out the wazoo.The game fundamentally misunderstands what the point of these types of games are.First, the game isn't working properly on a technical level. There are game crashing bugs, there are skill bugs, there are map bugs, there are multiplayer bugs. Fighting bugs makes the combat system unplayable.You'll run into lag in multiplayer, where the players exploring will cause the entire game to just stop doing anything while it's generating the new environment. You will run through empty caves where no minerals have yet spawned, no chests have appeared, no enemies appear and where you can't dig or place torches because the game is lagging behind too heavily. Then you'll hear your multiplayer companion swear over skype because they're suddenly unable to do anything.Secondly, the building and crafting portion of the game is completely unnecessary. You're delegated to progressing through the standard crafting tiers through the standard way of upgrading your standard crafting stations, getting the standard four weapons and the standard three armor parts. That's it. The rest is reskins with new stats, not changing a damned thing. You use the sword/spear, who work exactly the same, the bow or the wand. Nothing new, nothing exciting, nothing ever changing.You don't build a base, because why would you? You don't spend any time in your base, you don't have anything to fill your base with, you can take your crafting tables with you instead when you do the arbitrary digging for copper->iron->silver->gold. There's no discovery to be made anywhere along the line.Thirdly, combat doesn't work. At all. You trigger an enemy's attack, counter, rinse and repeat. Or you shoot at it from afar until it dies. Or, you build a one block wall and hit the enemy through it. This is of course on the rare occasions when enemies spawn at all, and on the even rarer occasion when they're not bugged out. The enemies get progressively higher stats as you walk the planet, but they're the same and their power levels are completely unpredictable. You can be around a lvl 7-9 crystal and suddenly face a lvl 24 enemy. It's stupid.Fourthly, you never have any goals to strive for. You do, what, exploration? Why? To find what? You don't need anythin, you don't really want to do anything. You dig? Why? To get iron instead of copper for the work station upgrade? Yawn. You come across a red crystal with a dungeon instance? Skip it. Why bother?Don't get this game. Crea isn't worth it. Get Terraria. Get Starbound if it's on sale. Hell, get Minecraft before you get this. It's no good.EDIT: I did play the beta 1.4 patch, and that is the version of the game I've reviewed. The beta version of the patch was released on the 7th of June and I played it 3 days later, and my achievments were unlocked on the 10th of June to prove it."
,Not Recommended,280520,31350224,Posted: 24 April,all,Klokinator,"It's really hard to explain just how bad this game is. My issue was that despite my early misgivings, I kept thinking the game would 'open up' after the 4 hours mark, and so I kept playing. Once I reached the first boss, that was when I knew...This game suffers from No Man's Sky syndrome.""What is NMS Syndrome?"", you may ask. Great question! It's a special sort of suffering that comes about when a game has just enough intrigue and promise to make you play past Steam's refund period, and then instantly drops off afterwards.The problems with this game are not going to be fixed without a total rework and transformation into a totally different game, but let me go ahead and spend my time explaining to you just how extensive they are.Music:This might seem to be a silly thing to start with, but my god the music in this game is the blandest most boring OST I have ever heard. It's tough to even call it music, honestly. This was always my biggest problem with it. Once you realize there is no 'action' in the game and it's truly a slow, plodding, boring experience, the music begins to make sense, but by then you've already lost all hope.If anything could start to make a dent in the playability of this game, making the music more interesting would be a big first step. Compare this to Terraria, which I consider the gold standard for indie game music. The music changes based on where you are in a planet, and it not only fits the general mood of an area, it also can help set the mood, like when you enter the Dungeon for the first time.Crea? The bosses don't even have different music. It's the same bland overworld track you've been listening to for 3 hours straight!Night-time/Day-time? Same music!Underground? Hey, the music changes a little bit! Too bad it's still boring.TL:DR, the music in this game is below sub-par, it might as well not even be there.User Interaction:One of the reasons I bought this game was because of the big lauded User Interface upgrade that I saw so much about and how excited people were for it. Guess what?...it's good. Like, the UI isn't bad at all.But the control scheme for this game is the worst thing I have experienced barring $0.99 games being resold from 1995 on Steam. I don't even know how to explain this, but here goes.1. You have two main 'control schemes' you must use. One is for exploration, the other is for combat.2. Each control scheme has a sort of alternate scheme you can switch from. As an example, you can have a melee/ranged and a magic loudout for your character, then your other scheme will be for exploration with magic spells to detect ore and such.3. So let's say you're playing with your sword and bow scheme. LMB will likely attack with the sword, and RMB will charge up and shoot your arrow. Want to switch to magic? Maybe you, like me, binded it to scroll-wheel-down. But if you want to switch to exploration mode, with your pickaxe and torches and stuff? That's atotally different button.4a. It gets better. The buttons you need to press change depending on what mode you're in. For example, in exploration mode, if you have a spell like the 'locate ore' spell on your hotbar in the '4' position, pressing 4 does not activate the spell. Instead, after pressing 4, you have to press RMB to activate it!4b. But let's say you're in combat mode, with your wands in hand and spells at the ready with Fireball tagged to the 4 slot. Pressing '4' DOES cast the spell! WHAT?!5a. Your actions against the lower hotbars also change depending on what menu you are viewing. For example, let's say you're in combat mode and there's an enemy coming. You don't have any of your inventory/character/talent windows or etc open, so if you right-click on fireball on your quick menu, it will cast Fireball.5b. But then let's say that you DO have an inventory or talent menu open... if you don't realize this and right-click on Fireball... it willdelete the god-damn spell from your hotbar! The enymy was already close by, now you have to frantically open up your talent menu, scroll to the fireball spell, drag it to your hotbar, close the menu, then right-click it again to cast it! Oops, you died!6. This one is more agregious, because of how asinine it is. In Exploration Mode, left clicking removes an object or mines a tile... and right click places one. Further, when you pluck comething out of your inventory, like a crafting table, and you then right click to place it... it doesn't place it! You often have to right-click twice! God forbid you left-click instead, you'll be baffled as to why you can't place this item down.Oh no! An enemy is attacking! You're in exploration mode underground, and you need to switch to your weapons in a hurry! What do you do? In your panic, you hit scroll-wheel-down, but alas... that switches to your alternate exploration loadout. So you hit your other button and now you're in magic mode... but oops! You forgot to place a torch somewhere so now you're in total darkness! (Unlike in Terraria, you can't hold shift for a split second to illuminate your surroundings with a torch in your inventory)You quicklly press the other button and swap your loadout to melee since this is CQC, but you're still totally blind. Swinging wildly, you quickly die. Or you try to run blindly, fall off a ledge, and take a ridiculous amount of fall damage.All I'm saying is that the control scheme in this game is abominable. But even all of what I've said pales in comparison to the next point...""""""Sandbox"""""" Progression:You know what I think makes Terraria great? You can be as good as you want at the game and it's all skill based. Sure, you might only be doing one-damage to the boss with each arrow you fire, but you're still actually damaging him. In Crea, you will often be fighting enemies at a much higher level than you and not be damaging them at all. Let's dive into core gameplay.Leveling Up:In Crea, as you perform an activity, you gain EXP for that thing. You have Arms, magic, exploration, crafting, and gathering.Arms is your physical attacks and such. This includes melee and ranged weapons like bows. (All right, just bows. No guns or anything cool.)Magic is obviously stuff related to magic, mostly meaning spells.Exploration is gained literally by walking around, and boosted by walking in areas you haven't been before, moreso in high level areas. This category also includes mobility upgrades like a double jump and sprinting.Crafting is leveled by crafting items, researching, etc. It not only allows you to refine items better, but get better sell prices and such.Gather is gained when you pick up items, dig in the ground, etc. It includes a few 'spells' that allow you to see ore and treasure chests and stuff, plus lots of upgrades for mining speed and etc.So the fundamental issue with leveling, especially in Crea, is that it just flatly locks you out of everything. In Terraria, double jumps can be obtained by finding a cloud in a bottle, and you might literally luck out and find those in a surface level chest five minutes into the game. In Crea, you're guaranteed 5 hours of grinding before you gain such a simple thing.But the real issue is what leveling and stats do to the gameplay experience. Crea has leveled zones, meaning the further you are from spawn, the stronger the enemies are, to the point of just one-shotting you. Three of your leveling traits gain you zero combat survivability. The only way to increase your actual player level is to grind in combat by attacking every single enemy you see, and it takes a LONG time........I hit the character limit for steam reviews. I really wanted to continue ripping this game to shreds but now I'm bored. Fantastic, that was effort wasted. Didn't know the limit existed."
76561198012567641,Not Recommended,280520,29663591,Posted: 2 February,all,mo123567,"I was going to start another game of Terraria when I decided that I have played that game so much that maybe a similar but fresh experience was in order. That's what I was hoping to find with Crea. Here is what I found:The leveling system seemed like a nice addition but quickly starts to feel formulaic when you realize that you are just fighting the same few monsters with the same strategies over and over as they level up along with you... until you learn how to abuse the quake spell to kill things from a distance. This may sound like a cheap solution but it is pretty hard to fight against enemies, some of which can do scummy things like hide and shoot at you from in the walls among other things that you have to avoid while combattng the most difficult enemy in the game: THE LAG. This game lags so much that I often find myself staring at the screen waiting to regain control of my character.In addition to the lag, this game is full of bugs and issues that should have been caught with even a minimal amount of playtesting. Sometimes I log in and am spawned in complete darkness in the ground. I defeat a dungeon only to think I'm trapped until I realize that the crystal needed to exit is hidden in a lava lake. Items randomly get deleted from my inventory. The mod system is a mess and easily breaks your world.If this game were in early development, I could understand all the issues and I might have even looked forward to seeing how it came along but as a game that had it's full release over half a year ago, I can't recommend buying it. I guess I'll start that Terraria world after all."
76561198053653124,Recommended,280520,30805859,Posted: 28 March,all,Agrias Oaks,"Thus far this game has exceeded ALL of my expectations! I came in expecting another build, craft, survive, game much like Terraria and Starbound...that's not what this is.The combat system feels much more skill based at times (timing combos for more damage, knowing the reach on your next combo swing, and even buffing prior to combat or mid combat). The crafting system is more along the lines of Starbound, you have to unlock the recipes, and you'll spend plenty of time unlocking all recipes. The building feels familiar, and while there are no impending threats (pirates, goblins, etc... attacking your base, or even zombies at night or even ANYTHING moving to attack you) there are plenty of enemies and they can certainly be difficult, especially when you're out numbered!The dev, Jasson, is AWAYS diligently working on the game and is very friendly and transparent! It's rare to find a dev as open as Jasson, and I definitely recommend checking his stream out on twitch sometime!10/10 Yes, play this one!"
,Recommended,280520,20498267,"Posted: 12 January, 2016",all,Lima,"After 20 hours of gameplay in 3 days, it's well past time for me to give some feedback. Please note that this may contain spoilers for newer players.Combat:The combat system is intricate and diverse. You can go from being a magic-wielding battlemage to a deadly archer to a brutal melee character, with no long-term effects if alternating between different playstyles. You have a lot of unique skills that can be used to kill enemies, defend yourself, or heal yourself. There are 4 different weapons; bows, swords, spears, and magic.Bows are the most powerful of the 4 in terms of damage. The ammo is fairly simple to get assuming the player isn't using the bow for every minor encounter.Pros:Easy-to-get ammoHigh damage outputCons:Occasionally on shooting, the trajectory is a good bit off of what one would expect. You can more easily see what I am describing when shooting down at enemies.Swords are the next weapon and the better of the two melees. They are dangerous to use in comparison to other weapon types.Pros:Infinite usageCons:Limited to ground or low-flying enemiesDangerous to use, even with melee armorMagic is the third strongest of the 4 in my opinion. It is diverse in terms of skills, simple in terms of weapon types.Pros:Ranged attacksUtility and damage skillsCons:Wands have short ranged attacks that make them difficult to useLow damage outputSpears are the final weapon. They are not very good at all.Pros:Cons:Hard to use; aiming at enemies that are in you is practically impossible.The combat weapons are interesting as there are a lot of them to use. Swords will limit players' abilities to button mash as there is a better way to swing that involves timing and precision rather than button-mashing. The stamina limitation is understandable but a little bit unnecessary for attacks, in my opinion. The magic wands and skills drain stamina rather than mana or something else of the sort, which makes little sense. Although this avoids confusion, it isn't very realistic.Crafting:The crafting system is clever and fun. Crea has modifiers just like Terraria, however these modifiers are applied to weapons via a system called Chaos crafting. After playing a short minigame, the end quality that you score is then used to determine the quality of the modifier you receive. The system is interesting and better than Terraria's reforging system as it doesn't involve mass amounts of currency and the end quality of an item can be controlled through skill progression.In addition to Chaos crafting, the other notable mechanic of crafting is research. Researching a recipe is necessary in order to craft it, and the researching is done by consuming crafting ingredients. The system only allows you to research items that for sure are used in something, and as far as my experiences go the consumption of an item guarantees you are on step closer to the end of a recipe. This system is a great way to create progression and it is a clever one overall.Bosses:The bosses in Crea aren't the best in my honest opinion. Although they are unique, the actual implementation is lacking.Sano:Sano is the first boss you will fight, generally speaking. The fight involves you to bring down the shield around her by using her own attack on her, and then you attack her like crazy during the 10 seconds before she resummons her shield. The fight is fun and challenging. The part about her that I don't like is that there isn't a clear goal to go to after defeating her.Dormian:Dormian is the second boss in the game. Dormian is the opposite of Sano in that the goals after the boss fight are clear but the actual boss fight is poor. The reason I say this is because the boss fight comes down to attacking the right clone of him to bring his health down. The actual attacks he uses are balanced and fun, however figuring out how to attack him is very complicated. After already defeating him, I still don't completely understand the logic behind which is attackable and which isn't. It came down to a game of attacking random ones so that when they all shifted again one of the ones I attacked would lower the health of the others.Miscellaneous:-Numerous bugs are in the game, however numerous bugs are being fixes every single day by the developer.-Performance issues that include massive drops in FPS that happen periodically. Performance was greatly increased over Weekly Update #23, however.-A longer tutorial that detailed parts of the game beyond Chaos crafting (remnas, for example) would be much appreciated by newer players. This is especially important due to the lack of an up-to-date wiki.-The developer, Jasson is very active and friendly. Numerous bugs are fixed each day and the developer is very helpful on the forums. It is great for the future of the game to have such a developer working on it and helping its community."
