76561198025835279,Recommended,280520,33655374,Posted: 19 July,all,Eloar,"It's an absolute shame every platform has seemingly done away with star ratings -- though I think I get it, it's a way to drive sales.Since, I'd recommend this game, but I'd only give it about a3 - 3.5 / 5 rating. It's an average game.The first 20 or so hours of this game are amazing -- though I'd imagine this number might be lower if you accidentally discover what you're supposed to do first, or choose to play in a medium sized world first.My spoiler-free review is this: this game will feel very familiar if you've played any crafting game before (quickly becoming my favorite genre) -- but, unfortunately, Crea doesn't really offer anything new in the genre. It does streamline certain things (things like weapons and gear do not have durability), and there is a heavy emphasis on fighting -- which isn't a bad thing, except, ultimately, it ends up feeling like fighting for fighting's sake.There is lore in this game, but it is not presented in a forthright way -- thus there is little-to-no incentive to care about it.My spoiler free review is this: if you're interested in a quick, 2D RPG-light, crafting/adventuring fix to play with a friend or loved one, I highly recommend this.But if you're looking for something deeper, look elsewhere. I'm almost 40 hours in, and while I still enjoy it, about 15 or so hours ago the charm wore off, and now I am more or less chasing achievements where fun happens too infrequently.Spoilers:This game's fun quickly diminishes when you kind of figure out the pattern: research everything, fight the boss, rise and repeat. Magic feels underwhelming and not as fun as melee. The game tends to flood the screen with bad guys, and magic is just too slow and weak -- I know there are ways to circumvent this via crafting; however, early game will dictate a player's choice, and most likely they will feel obligated to go toward a melee build.There are too few areas and too few monsters -- there should definitely be just as much stuff going on up in the clouds as there is underground -- but there isn't -- in fact, in my large-generated world, I only got one or two areas where there was stuff happening high up -- and by the time I discovered it, it was nothing new -- no new textures and no new monsters.The game needs more stuff to do besides just level -- ultimately everything comes down to: what is your level via combat. So there is a large incentive placed on leveling up your character as opposed to building a house, etc.There needs to be incentives for crafting housing items (maybe during the night monsters get a lot stronger and way more aggressive?); also, there should be reasons for farming -- there are shears in the game, and when I discovered that, I thought I'd be able to mate and feed sheep, and maybe find other animals I could essentially farm -- but there was no ""gate"" item, no way to easily hear sheep (for fun I grappled a bunch of them up into my ""above ground"" ""farm"".This game would benefit from quests, more mechanics, and more mysteries to uncover."
