76561198018811171,Recommended,280520,23479128,"Posted: 9 June, 2016",all,Fish Bazooka,"I will continue to update my review as I play.Crea came out of nowhere and blew past most of the games I've played. Don't miss out on this gem. The soundtrack is amazing and the art style is grabbing. So far this game has been VERY user friendly for me. The hud/layout is easy to navigate and butter smooth. The tutorial system as you play is very helpful and won't leave you blind. It's easy to get familiar quickly. You gain TP through different categories depending on what you do (fighting, magic, exploring, crafting, harvesting/mining I believe, etc.). TP can be used in each of these categories to purchase talents (active & passive). Also, you gain xp from creatures you kill. The combat is crisp but I wouldn't call it fluid. When you level up, you gain stat points you can distribute with about 7 or 8 different options (att, def, int, luck, agi, stamina, etc.) which I love because that's really what makes every character different (all talents can be maxed by any character but stats are unique). Anything and everything is destructable & craftable. The most similiar game to Crea is Terraria which I enjoyed playing."
,Recommended,280520,23481189,"Posted: 10 June, 2016",all,Zincoshine,"In may 2011, terraria was released, pioneering the 2D sandbox genre. At its time it was a pretty minimalistic game with no story and limited content, but over the years it gained more and more content that eventually made terrraria one of the most underpriced games on steam.With the success of Terraria, other developers began taking an interest in making their own 2D sandbox games. There were a lot of promising ones that went into early access, but they quickly found themselves unable to compete with terraria that already had a good headstart and was continously being updated. Those that did make it out of early access have all been failures.... that is until now. 5 years after the release of terraria, Crea has just become the first good 2D sandbox game to be released since terraria. Crea is better than terraria in some ways but also worse and I will explain in detail all theseHere is how Crea is better than terraria:- Crea has a backstory that gets revealed as the game progresses.- Crea has slightly better graphics.- Crea has a leveling up and research system that creates a sense of progress and pretty much eliminates the need for a guide NPC.- Crea has a tutorial that helps guide the player in the very beginning. luckily, the game is fairly intuitive once you get used to the new system in comparison to terraria.- Crea has better native modding support than Terraria.- Crea does not require a wiki in order to play and discover the world on your own.Here is how terraria is better:- Terraria is underpriced, crea is fairly priced.- Terraria has more content, although this could change since terraria has reached its limits whereas Crea will continue to get updates going forward.- Terraria performs better, lower PC requirements, more optimised code.- Terraria's music is slightly better.- terraria's controls are slightly better.All in all, if you are looking for a 2D sandbox with a more RPG feel to it, Crea is recommended over Terraria. If you are a fan of terraria who is looking for something new but similar, Crea is recommended for you. If you want more freedom in what you do in the game, dislike a RPG progression system, or want a lot of content then terraria is recommended over Crea."
