,Not Recommended,280520,23569460,"Posted: 15 June, 2016",all,Pandemonium Knight,"Crea is a 2D sidescrolling game with building and slow deliberate combat. It is similar in many respects to Terraria and Starbound. It's a decent game for what it is, but it should still be in early access as it is buggy and lacks polish. As it is now, I cannot recommend this game. If you'd like to play a game like this, you're probably better off playing Terraria as the devs there have had a great deal of time to refine the game.Pros+Talent points are constantly being gained, so your character is always improving as you play.+Procedurally generated worlds.+Built in mod support. If the game is able to maintain dedicated players, then it should have a good deal of extra free content.+Skills that enhance mobility, such as sprinting, ledge grabs, and double jumps can be obtained quite quickly.+Fast travel system. Saves you from retreading the same ground over and over again.+When compared to Terraria, digging is more satisfying earlier on due to upgrades allowing the mining of multiple tiles, making it less tedious to dig through areas.+Spells that you are able to access early on make it easy to find ore and chests.+No contact damage on most, if not all enemies, so you can't just take damage by bumping into them.Cons-Visual feedback is a bit lacking on spells.-Enemies are neither knocked backed or staggered by your attacks, making combo attacks less than usefull and making ranged combat seem like an objectively better option.-Enemies are sparse in the underground and tend to ignore you. There isn't much down there aside from the occasional crystal that teleports you to a dungeon, small rooms with chests in them, and of course, ores.-Only THREE options in the settings menu: volume, fullscreen options, and resolution. Sound effects and music aren't even separated, so if you want to listen to your own music or a video in the background, you're going to have to mute the sound entirely, or let the sounds overlap.-I've encountered a bug that has destroyed all my furniture, chests, NPCs, and many of my waystones (used for fast travel). The bug happened after teleporting back from the first(?) boss. I was able to pick up all of the furniture and items in the chests, but the Renma cores (a fairly valuable and rare resource) used to create the NPCs and my waystones were lost. I'd imagine there is a way to create new waystones, but I'm not sure how far along it is in the game.-Very small weapon variety at least in the early game. There are a few different spells, but not many.-Most chests (aside from ones in realm crystals and dungeons) locked and you have to rely on random drops to get keys for them or use lockpicks.-A lot of the gear you get from chests have high level requirements for the time you're able to get them, so you'll be waiting a while before you can even use them."
,Recommended,280520,11241007,"Posted: 14 July, 2014",all,inaliz,"Crea is another game in the 2d adventure Sandbox realm. Very similar to Terraria, I would say Crea is most like Terraria as far as a successor, at least so far. Where Starbound is more about exploration, Crea is more about sticking to the core and adding more mechanics. It has rpg like progression where you gain skill points by using that specific skill line. For instance, if you shoot something with an arrow your physical attack tree will gain experience. The same goes for crafting, buff/healing, sorcery and gathering. When they level up each skill line you gain access to new, more powerful skills.It has a big emphasis on researching materials in the world in order to unlock new recipes. You will need to keep exploring deeper and further to progress to higher tier items. The world is very similar to terraria where you can find chests and all kinds of loot in various places. It has a crystal system in the game as a fast travel device. So once you find the crystals you are able to travel between them for a small price. They are located above and below ground. There is also an advanced research system in place that requires finding recipes from monsters.The soundtrack is amazing. Crea has the look and feel of the game down as well. The soundtrack is put together so well, it is very relaxing and perfect for the game style. Very reminiscent to EVE Online's awesome ambient soundtrack. Hopefully they will make it even longer before release. The UI is very slick and easy to use although for the amount of spells/item combinations it does need a little tweaking in my opinion. Having ten hotkeys and then each having a right/left click bind has been done over and over and I would really like to see a new and efficient action bar/UI implemented in this genre. Or at least a big improvement.At this point in development the most you can do is craft the highest ier items and face one boss. I pretty much got as far as that which was 20 hours of gameplay. I enjoyed it thuroughly and am eager to see what they will be bringing to the game by release. Seeing that the game is early on in develoment still and in early access I would give it an 8.5/10. It will have to do a lot of work to maintain or beat that by release though. The game is also highly modable but I haven't checked anything like that out yet.Things I would really like to see before release.The world needs to be filled with different dungeons/exploration triggers and bosses/special monsters. Content basically and it's early access so I'm sure this is in the works. With these 2d sandbox games the funnest part is the mystery of what you could find.I like the skill progression system. But, as of right now the whole thing is kind of pointless because there are no decisions to make. You unlock the next 3 skills and then to level them up until you hit the next skill unlock level. The skills themselves need a lot of polishing as well and they need to, look cooler.The UI needs something to make it more efficient or intuitive. Is it ok now? Sure, but it doesn't improve on the genre's adopted UI or do anything new."
