,Recommended,280520,23604823,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,Jesonomi,"I think this game falls under a ""wait and see"" category, even though I did mark this as a recommended review. I decided on this because while there are notable flaws, my overall experience wasn't negative and the developer seems to be constantly working on the game. I picked Crea up during its -10% release sale. The developer has said the next sale will be in December 2016, at ~25% off.I suppose the first game people jump to in comparison is Terraria. I loved Terraria. I rarely think about Terraria when playing this game. I would draw more similarities to Starbound. I didn’t like Starbound, but Crea doesn’t draw out the same dullness I felt from there.Crea has two leveling systems. The first is the general character/combat level that increases as you kill monsters. Your stats go up, you get a point to allocate, simple enough. The second is the Talent system. Whenever you take an action, you have a chance to gain experience in a corresponding Talent, Arms (Weapons), Syle (Magic), Gather, Craft, and Explore. It’s a very nice system that feels rewarding… aside from Craft. I’ll talk about that later.Graphics are nice, I like the more subtle colors compared to Terraria, while still remaining crisper than Starbound. Music is nice and accompanies the slower gameplay very well. Even though the gameplay is slower, I never really felt like my character itself was too slow. I know in Terraria the initial startup movement is extremely painful, but it feels good in Crea. Even with a Sprinting talent unlocked, I often forget about it simply because the normal walking speed is a great pace. The time before a grappler can be obtained is smoothed out with a Ledge Grab talent, and you can unlock a Double Jump talent farther in. Way Crystals are sprinkled throughout the world, and you can harvest them and create your own. You can choose any Way Crystal as your spawn point and teleport back using warp crystals that grow around Way Crystals. These grow back in pretty large numbers, so you’re never really low on them.Now, Craft… it just feels bad after a certain point. At first, you’re blowing through it like every other talent. And then it stops. Why? Because you’ve already crafted what you needed. So you’ll find yourself running around, have all your other Talents continue going up in level… while the game is waiting for you to grind Craft. And it’s not supposed to be just random junk either. Nope. You have to craft things close to your level to actually gain exp. And only sometimes, because gaining Talent exp is through chance. Now, I will say I can’t tell if there’s a level indicator on non-level-restricted items, and I’ve seen some mentions about candle crafting working (which is somewhat cheap), but the whole idea just feels very contrasting with the other talents. It’s usually huge spikes in research followed by large droughts, you have to actively work on it with some vague concepts, while all the other Talents just happen, and it feels tightly linked to progression.Overall, though, if you happen to look up Craft help and get through it’s not horrible. Crea has potential. Multiplayer needs to be ironed out but singleplayer seems fun."
