,Recommended,280520,23556597,"Posted: 14 June, 2016",all,I'm Still Gonna Send It!,"Let's make this abundantly clear. This game does have it's bugs, and there's a number of them; but that shouldn't be the absolute decided factor between picking up this game in my opinion. Jasson (Siege Games main developer) does a weekly live stream where he let's players chat and discuss various issues with the game. He is, without a doubt, 100% on top of all issues that are being addressed.Now, in my experience thus far, I actually haven't came across a single bug that's been mentioned by other players. More specifically, Audio/Graphic issues. I have 14.4 hours (as of this review) and I've yet to experience one hiccup. The game itself has enough content for a CASUAL gamer. You have boss fights, you have character progression, you have researching/crafting. There's plenty of pros to this game in it's current state, and that will only continue to grow.One thing I see that's mentioned quite a bit is the learning curve. Here's what you need to understand. The game is new, and the fanbase is relatively small currently (Approx. ~1000 players). The Wiki doesn't have much information, so you're really reliant on exploring the game yourself and actually taking the time to LEARN it. If that's something you don't want to do, and you just want a mindless tutorial you're going to skip over anyways, then this isn't the game for you. The best way to learn the game currently IS TO PLAY IT.At first, I was extremely intimidated by the game. I spawned next to a crystal with what seemed to be a teleporting option; I quickly ignored it and moved on. A few hours in I really started to understand it's purpose. For nearly 10 hours of gameplay, I had NO idea you could use spells such as proficiencies, in passive mode. I kept switching to attack mode to cast my spells. Again, I figured this out because I PLAYED the game.TL;DR:The game isn't in bad shape at all. There's major and minor bugs, but every game will have those. Stick with the developer, report the bugs, and I PROMISE this will make Terraria seem like a childs game. Also, on a side note. Jasson is the only developer, and on his stream June 13th, he mentioned wanting to hire a C++ coder to help fix bugs and improve content. One thing I truly admired about him was his excitement seeing people on Twitch playing his game. He's clearly working his very hardest to listen to players and fix big issues. He took questions/issues DIRECTLY from viewers on Twitch and fixed them right in front of your eyes. The guy shows a lot of promise, and so does this game. I highly recommend picking it up while it's $15. One thing I do recommend (this is for Siege Games), ask some big players of your game to help expand the content of your Wiki. Provide starter guides, more explanations, and clarifications on items/crafting/chaos. Let your players help other players."
